data.content:
Three EF Core 10 breaking changes hit your code directly:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes a regular lambda, not an expression tree

Your entire manual `Expression.Lambda`/`Expression.Call` construction no longer compiles. Replace it with a simple lambda:

```csharp
// .NET 10 — dramatically simplified
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

No expression tree API needed at all — conditionals work directly inside the lambda body now.

---

### 2. Complex type column names are uniquified / nested paths changed

Two changes combine here:

- **Shared property names** (e.g. `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street`) now get a numeric suffix to disambiguate. A migration will try to rename columns.
- **Nested complex types** now use the full path: `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` maps to `Payment_BillingAddress_City` (was `BillingAddress_City`).

**Fix:** Pin existing column names explicitly so no migration rename is generated:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, a =>
    {
        a.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street");
        // repeat for other properties
    });
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, a =>
    {
        a.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street");
    });
});

// For nested complex types:
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment, p =>
    {
        p.ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress, a =>
        {
            a.Property(a => a.City).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
        });
    });
});
```

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method gained a `string logCommandText` parameter. Your class won't compile until you add it:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection, DbCommand command,
        DbContext context, Guid commandId, Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)          // ← new parameter (redacted SQL)
    {
        // Use logCommandText for safe logging (constants redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual SQL
    }
}
```

Add the same parameter to **all** implemented methods (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.).

---

**Summary:** The `ExecuteUpdateAsync` change is the biggest win — it eliminates all that expression tree plumbing. The other two are mechanical signature/config fixes. After applying these, generate a new migration (`dotnet ef migrations add FixColumnNames`) to verify no unintended column renames remain.
